<br>
I chose Jesus Christ as my Lord and Saviour when I was 7 years old because I knew I wanted to be a part of His eternal family.  I wanted Him to live in my heart so that I could be with Him in heaven when I died.<br>
<br>
Has that reason changed at all?<br>
<br>
That fundamental reason has never <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>changed</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, but my reasons continue to grow:<br>
<br>
6th grade through 12th grade:  I continued to choose Christ because His Word alone gave me the foundation I needed to know what was right and wrong, with regards to morality.  He alone gave me the strength to resist peer pressure, and the peace to stand alone.<br>
<br>
college years:  My relationship with Christ, my faith grew ever stronger when I realized how many young people battled with depression/apathy.  I continued to choose Christ because of the strong convictions I experienced when I made poor choices, and the releasing of guilt through His forgiveness.<br>
<br>
early married life:  I continued to choose Christ because He was my only sure foundation.  Getting married, beginning a new job and moving away from home brought enormous challenges to me; the Rock that is Jesus Christ was, at times, the only stable aspect to my life.  I also learned what it meant to grow in our relationship through fasting during these years.  Also, a significant miracle occured which saved my sister's life, which only increased my faith.<br>
<br>
birth of our children-present:  I chose/continue to choose Christ because, oh,....for so many reasons.  I fear Him, in that we have been given such an awesome responsibility with raising our children; I love Him because only my Father walks with me in dark times and alleviates my fears and worries; I praise Him for all the blessings and trials I have;  I am amazed at the mystery of our Heavenly Creator, science and philosophy have helped me to realize that. <br>
<br>
I choose Christ because nothing, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>nothing</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> else in this world makes sense...there is no peace, no comfort, no security, no freedom, no light apart from the true Light of Christ.<br>
<br>
Sorry, didn't mean to write a book.  I guess I just don't have a short answer to your questions! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
